  "text": "Motivated in part by these previous studies, the Intercontinental Chemical Transport Experiment (INTEX-B: http: //www.espo.nasa.gov/intex-b, [CITATION_1] ) took place during spring 2006 (15 April-15 May) with the objective of characterizing the pollution flowing into the West Coast of the United States, particularly from Asia. A collaborative effort among NASA, NCAR and a variety of university research groups, INTEX-B produced data from several platforms (ground-based, aircraft, remote sensing, model, etc.) . Among these was the University of Washington's Duchess aircraft which flew seven flights off the coast of Washington state; results from this analysis are presented by [CITATION_2] . Through an investigation of transPacific transport pathways, INTEX-B provided an opportunity to better understand the meteorological aspects of interannual variability in trace gases. Of particular interest during INTEX-B was the transport of Asian emissions to western North America.",
